{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01XTWz5Ln8kL55XQKNQKhw7c","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything checks out. Summary:\n\n**Root cause:** RabbitMQ was already correctly exposing Prometheus metrics (port 15692, `/metrics`, `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin enabled via `rabbitmq-config` ConfigMap) via the `rabbitmq` and `rabbitmq-headless` Services. Prometheus, however, had no scrape job for RabbitMQ at all — its `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only scraped itself.\n\n**Fix:** Updated the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a `rabbitmq` scrape job using a native `dns_sd_configs` (DNS-based service discovery, no CRDs/operators) pointed at the headless service `rabbitmq-headless.karma-rabbitmq-permission-sweep-marat-488c23f5-cluster-a.svc.cluster.local`, type `A`, port `15692`, `metrics_path: /metrics`. Since it's a headless Service (`clusterIP: None`, `publishNotReadyAddresses: true`), DNS resolves to all 3 pod IPs, giving Prometheus one target per RabbitMQ pod. Reloaded config via the existing `--web.enable-lifecycle` `/-/reload` endpoint (no pod restart needed).\n\n**Verified:**\n- `/api/v1/targets` shows 3 `rabbitmq` job targets, all `health: \"up\"` at ports `15692`.\n- `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` returns 3 samples, all value `1`.\n- RabbitMQ cluster remains healthy: 3/3 pods Running, `rabbitmqctl cluster_status` shows all 3 nodes as Running disk nodes."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1882,"cache_read_input_tokens":59251,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1882},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95994337-1f85-405e-8a79-baed1034bbc5","uuid":"3ffe85dc-3cd6-40f4-bfef-e339463bfde2","request_id":"req_011Ccai57UQdkvXr1fAfFzgL"}
